ting system almost entire operating system written c programming language that allowed unix reach numerous platforms many clones unix have arisen over years which linux most popular having displaced sus-certified unix on many server platforms since its inception early 1990s contents overview history standards components impact o free unix unix-like variants o arpanet branding see also references further reading external links overview version unix research unix ancestor all modern unix systems unix was originally meant be convenient platform for programmers developing software be run on on other systems rather than for non-programmer users system grew larger operating system started spreading academic circles users added their own tools system shared them with colleagues unix was designed be portable multi-tasking multi-user time-sharing configuration unix systems are characterized by various concepts use plain text for storing data hierarchical file system treating devices certain types inter-process communication ipc files use large number software tools small programs that can be strung together through command-line interpreter using pipes opposed using single monolithic program that includes all same functionality these concepts are collectively known unix philosophy brian kernighan rob pike summarize this unix programming environment idea that power system comes more from relationships among programs than from programs themselves by early 1980s users began seeing unix potential universal operating system suitable for computers all sizes unix environment client–server program model were essential elements development internet reshaping computing centered networks rather than individual computers both unix c programming language were developed by at&t distributed government academic institutions which led both being ported wider variety machine families than any other operating system under unix operating system consists many utilities along with master control program kernel kernel provides services start stop programs handles file system other common low-level tasks that most programs share schedules access avoid conflicts when programs try access same resource device simultaneously mediate such access kernel has special rights reflected division between user space kernel space microkernel concept was introduced effort reverse trend towards larger kernels return system which most tasks were completed by smaller utilities era when standard computer consisted hard disk for storage data terminal for input output i/o unix file model worked quite well most i/o was linear however modern systems include networking other new devices graphical user interfaces developed file model proved inadequate task handling asynchronous events such those generated by mouse 1980s non-blocking i/o set inter-process communication mechanisms were augmented with unix domain sockets shared memory message queues semaphores microkernel implementations functions such network protocols could be moved out kernel while conventional monolithic unix implementations have network protocol stacks part kernel history main article history unix ken thompson sitting dennis ritchie working together at pdp-11 pre-history unix dates back mid-1960s when massachusetts institute technology bell labs general electric were developing innovative time-sharing operating system called multics for ge-645 mainframe multics introduced many innovations but had many problems frustrated by size complexity multics but not by aims bell labs slowly pulled out project their last researchers leave multics ken thompson dennis ritchie m d mcilroy j f ossanna decided redo work on much smaller scale name unics uniplexed information computing service pronounced eunuchs pun on multics multiplexed information computer services was initially suggested for project new operating system was emasculated multics peter h salus credits peter neumann with pun while brian kernighan claims coining for himself adds that no one can remember who came up with final spelling unix dennis ritchie also credits kernighan unix was rewritten c programming language migration from assembly higher-level language c resulted much more portable software requiring only relatively small amount machine-dependent code be replaced when porting unix other computing platforms bell labs produced several versions unix that are collectively referred research unix first source license for unix was sold faculty at university illinois department computer science uiuc graduate student greg chesson who had worked on unix kernel at bell labs was instrumental negotiating terms this license during late 1970s early 1980s influence unix academic circles led large-scale adoption unix bsd system v by commercial startups including sequent hp-ux solaris aix xenix late 1980s at&t unix system laboratories sun microsystems developed system v release svr4 which was subsequently adopted by many commercial unix vendors 1990s unix-like systems grew popularity linux bsd distributions were developed through collaboration by worldwide network programmers apple released darwin that became core macos operating system unix operating systems are widely used modern servers workstations mobile devices standards common desktop environment cde part cose initiative beginning late 1980s open operating system standardization effort now known posix provided common baseline for all operating systems ieee based posix around common structure major competing variants unix system publishing first posix standard early 1990s separate but very similar effort was started by industry consortium common open software environment cose initiative which eventually became single unix specification sus administered by open group starting open group ieee started austin group provide common definition posix single unix specification which by had become open group base specification effort towards compatibility several unix system vendors agreed 